title: STRESS-STRAIN RELATIONSHIP OF REINFORCED CONCRETE SUBJECTED TO BIAXIAL TENSION. PAPER BY J.-Y.CHO, N.-S. KIM, N.-S. CHO, AND Y.-S. CHOUN. DISCUSSION.
authors: Peter H. Bischoff
abstract: This brief article comments on a study that of the tensile stress-strain relationship of reinforced concrete (RC) membrane elements. Extensive tests of RC panels with varying reinforcement ratios were performed to derive a reasonable constitutive law of the tensile stress-strain relationship of RC. Test results show that concrete carries substantial tensile stress even after initial cracking. In this discussion, Bischoff contends that the authors analysis of their results takes account of the reinforcing ratio but neglects the effect of shrinkage. Shrinkage can have a significant effect on both the member cracking load and tension stiffening contribution of concrete that is characterized by the average tensile stress in the concrete between cracks. Bischoff reminds readers that the relationships proposed by both the authors and himself are applicable to concrete reinforced with steel only.

title: Discussion of "Punching Shear Strength of Reinforced Concrete Slabs Strengthened with Glass Fiber-Reinforced Polymer Laminates" by Cheng-Chih Chen and Chung-Yan Li (With Closure)
authors: M Reze Esfahani; Vahid Moradi; Himat T. Solanki; Chandra Khoe
abstract: A discussion of the aforementioned article, published in this journal (July-August 2005) is presented. Two separate brief articles are presented, with the authors responding to both papers simultaneously. The first paper, with the discussers of M. Reza Esfahani and Vahid Moradi, have questions concerning the proposed equations, and request that the authors confirm their calculations. The second response, with discussion from Himat Solanki and Chandra Khoe, provides a number of specific comments on issues such as inconclusive test results and typographical errors. In response to the first paper, the authors correct an error to a table in the original paper, and discuss the calculated strains. For the second paper, the authors provide specific responses to the issues of concern.

title: EFFECTIVE TORSIONAL RIGIDITY OF REINFORCED CONCRETE MEMBERS. PAPER BY TAVIO AND SUSANTO TENG. DISCUSSION.
authors: Edss Filho; J. R. Figueiredo Filho
abstract: This brief article comments on a study that presented a simple procedure for calculating effective torsional rigidity of reinforced concrete (RC) members. The proposed method related torsional rigidity, an important parameter for 3-D analysis of RC structures, to the applied torque taking the effect of reinforcement into account. The method is applicable throughout the entire loading history from the uncracked state to the fully cracked state and even to the ultimate limit state. Comparison between the computed and experimental torque-twist curves showed that the proposed procedure for computing effective torsional rigidity is reasonably accurate. In this commentary, Filho and Filho contend that the original experimental data and conclusions are not precise. They describe their concerns and provide a data table that compares computed cracking torque with Hsu (1968) data. The original authors respond to each of the objectives outlined in this discussion, and present their own table that compares calculated cracking torques with Hsu's test data.

title: Longitudinal Steel Stresses in Beams Due to Shear and Torsion in AASHTO-LRFD Specifications: Discussion.
authors: Himat T. Solanki; Chandra Khoe
abstract: Accounting for the effects of shear and torsion (which cause diagonal cracks in concrete beams) on the reinforcing steel in concrete is necessary to ensure a safe design and to avoid the possibility of brittle failures. The current AASHTO-LRFD specifications and the Canadian A23.3 CSA building code use an alternative shear and torsion design method that requires a check on the adequacy of the longitudinal steel to resist the stresses not only from bending and axial loads, but also from shear and torsion. This discussion article comments on a recent study (Rahal, 2005) that evaluated this general method equation for the calculation of the stresses in the longitudinal steel in members with adequate transverse reinforcement. Longitudinal steel strain readings from tests were compared with the values calculated based on the general method equation for longitudinal force. Rahal concluded that the AASHTO's equation provides accurate estimates of the longitudinal force in nonprestressed beams. In their discussion Solanki and Khoe question why Rahal's equation does not address the compression and transverse reinforcement, but only relates to tensile reinforcement. The discussers provide some equations for the adequacy of the longitudinal and transverse reinforcement.

title: Estimation of AR Parameters in the Presence of Additive Contamination in the Infinite Variance Case
authors: Hossein Ali Niroumand
abstract: If we try to estimate the parameters of the AR process {Xn} using the observed process {Xn+Zn} then these estimates will be badly biased and not consistent but we can minimize the damage using a robust estimation procedure such as GMestimation. The question is does additive contamination affect estimates of “core” parameters in the infinite variance case to the same extent that it does in the finite variance case? We will see that if the contamination {Zn} has higher tails than the core process {Xn}, the estimation of parameters of the core process will not be greatly affected; that at least its consistency is preserved.

title: LIMITS OF REINFORCEMENT IN 2002 ACI CODE: TRANSITION, FLAWS, AND SOLUTION. PAPER BY ANTOINE E. NAAMAN. DISCUSSION.
authors: Jcm Toro
abstract: This brief article comments on a study in which examples were presented where the provisions of the 2002 ACI Code on limits of reinforcement in flexural members lead to unintended but erroneous conclusions. After an analysis of the causes of error, a simple, rational, and reliable solution was proposed that preserves the real intent of the Code and is likely to appeal to all users. In this discussion, Toro describes an error in Equation (A19). The bulk of this article consists of the original author (Naaman) responding to this correction and an earlier commentary (Sun and Tadros, same issue). The author redefines the two objections raised by Sun and Tadros, and responds to each. These objections revolve around the definition of effective depth, and the validity of ACI 2002 versus ACI 1999 Code provisions.

title: INVESTIGATION OF MINIMUM LONGITUDINAL REINFORCEMENT REQUIREMENTS FOR CONCRETE COLUMNS USING PRESENT-DAY CONSTRUCTION MATERIALS. PAPER BY PAUL H. ZIEHL, JEFFREY E. CLOYD, AND MICHAEL E. KREGER. DISCUSSION.
authors: Henry G. Russell
abstract: This brief article comments on a study that was carried out to assess the feasibility of reducing the current ACI Building Code and AASHTO Bridge Specification requirements for minimum longitudinal reinforcing steel in columns. The aim was to determine the effects of modern-day construction materials on minimum reinforcement requirements. In this discussion, Russell congratulates the authors on their research to reassess the minimal longitudinal reinforcement requirements for columns since materials and concrete strengths have changed considerably since the original research was performed. Russell then discusses conclusion number 3, in which the authors state that a reduction of the current ACI Code requirement is not justified by the study. Russell considers whether this conclusion is applicable to full-size columns in real structures. Appended to Russell's commentary is a response from the original authors in which they recommend caution in extrapolating from results of the testing program to full-size columns, especially for columns constructed with high-strength materials.

title: CONCRETE SHEAR STRENGTH: ANOTHER PERSPECTIVE. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Evan C Bentz; William L. Gamble; Prodromos D. Zararis
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by A.K. Tureyen and R.J. Frosch, published in this journal (Volume 100, Number 5, September/October 2003), is provided. The discussers commend the authors for their research dealing with simplified modeling of the shear behavior of reinforced concrete members without stirrups. With the experiments they conducted on slender beams reinforced with steel as well as fiber-reinforced polymer longitudinal bars, the authors have further confirmed the key role of the size of the depth of the compression zone on the shear strength of beams. However, the discussers have some serious concerns with the authors' method for modeling the shear strength of such members considering only shear cracking of the flexural compression of the beam, and also with other concepts in their presented analysis. In closure, the authors respond to the points of contention raised by the discussers.

title: Headed Studs in Concrete: State of the Art: Discussion
authors: M K Thompson; James O. Jirsa; J E Breen
abstract: Headed studs are smooth or deformed bars, usually short compared to the lengths of concrete members, with forged or welded heads for anchorage at one or both ends; they are used instead of conventional reinforcing bars anchored by hooks and bends. This commentary article discusses a recent study that describes several practical applications where the use of headed studs is appropriate (Ghali and Youakin, 2005). The authors noted that the main advantages of headed studs are simpler installation, less congestion of reinforcement, improved confinement, and more effective anchorage. They also contend that the use of a headed bar, as opposed to a bar with a hook, is advantageous in applications where there is demand for the yield strength at a section of the bar close to its end. In this commentary article, Thompson et al offer responses on five areas of the original study: cover dimensions, strut-and-tie modeling, the relative head area of headed bars, double-headed studs used as shear reinforcement in concrete I-beams, and the variety of heads currently available on the market. A closure by the original article's authors addresses each of these concerns.

title: Strength of Reinforced Concrete Bridge Decks Under Compressive Membrane Action. Discussion and Closure
authors: John Newhook; Baidar Bakht; Aftab A. Mufti; Gamil Tadros
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title, written by A. Hon et al. and published in this journal (Volume 102, Number 3, May-June 2005), is presented. The discussers state that the authors, in dealng with the subject of arching (or compressive membrane action) in bridge deck slabs, do not appear to make use of the considerable body of research conducted in North America and Japan which has been reported in easily-accessible technical literature. A number of points are raised related to the strengths and weaknesses of the original paper, and closure from the authors is provided on the discussers' comments.

title: CRACK WIDTH PREDICTION USING COMPATIBILITY-AIDED STRUT-AND-TIE MODEL. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: B.N. Singh
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by R.R.H. Zhu et al., published in this journal (Volume 100, Number 4, July/August 2003), is presented. The discusser commends the authors on their meticulously planned and scrupulously executed research program, which has furthered the scope of application of the strut-and-tie method. Several observations noted by the discusser are listed for clarification purposes. In closure, the authors respond to these 5 commented-upon areas of their paper.

title: Discussion of Fiber-Reinforced Polymer Strengthening of Concrete Bridges That Remain Open to Traffic
authors: Richard Andrew Barnes
abstract: This brief discussion article comments on a study of traffic loads applied to a reinforced concrete bridge during and after its strengthening with externally bonded fiber-reinforced polymer (FRP) reinforcement (W. Reed et al, 2005). The study included eight beams: seven of them were strengthened with a precured, unidirectional, carbon-fiber laminate strip that represented the materials used on an actual bridge. The variables tested included the intensity and frequency of load cycles applied during the epoxy-curing period, the thickness of the epoxy layer, and the thickness of the FRP strip. The study showed that for all of the traffic loads applied during and after installation no reduction in strengthening was seen. The experiment concluded that concrete bridges can be strengthened effectively even if they remain open to traffic during the procedure. In this commentary, Barnes reminds readers of the importance of considering the effects of traffic vibration during curing. Traffic vibration would have an effect on the strength of the adhesives typically used for this application. However, as the failure plane in an FRP strengthened concrete beam is typically within the concrete, the weakening of the adhesive does not affect the overall load capacity of the strengthened beams. Barnes concludes by cautioning that in other situations, such as steel beams, vibration from traffic loads may indeed lead to a reduction in ultimate capacity of the strengthened member.

title: COMBINED TORSION AND BENDING IN REINFORCED AND PRESTRESSED BEAMS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: H Solanki
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by K.N. Rahal and M.P. Collins, published in this journal (Volume 100, Number 2, March-April 2003), is provided. While the discusser commends the authors for an interesting paper, some 9 points are raised for further discussion. Closure from the authors is given.

title: FLEXURAL BEHAVIOR OF REINFORCED CONCRETE BEAMS STRENGTHENED WITH CARBON-FIBER-REINFORCED POLYMER LAMINATES AT DIFFERENT LEVELS OF SUSTAINING LOAD. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Renata. Kotynia
abstract: A discussion of a prior paper with the aforementioned title by Y. Shin and C. Lee, published in this journal (Volume 100, Number 2, March-April 2003), is presented. The discusser acknowledges the importance of conducting a large-scale experimental program to further the quality of strengthening reinforced concrete (RC) structures with carbon fiber-reinforced polymer (CFRP) laminates. The paper presents an innovative idea of strengthening at the different levels of sustaining loads. Significance of this work to help structural engineers in strengthening RC elements under sustained load in practice is stressed by the discusser. However, the discusser believes that certain aspects of the paper need to be reexamined, with some key details presented relating to steel reinforcement location from compression edge of the beam, cross section and Young's modulus of CFRP laminates, loading location, compression relationships, and tension steel reinforcement. Closure from the authors is also included.

title: Repair of Bridge Girders with Composites: Experimental and Analytical Validation: Discussion.
authors: Shiming Chen
abstract: This commentary discusses a laboratory study undertaken to investigate the flexural behavior of full-scale, damaged prestressed concrete (PC) bridge girders upgraded with externally bonded carbon fiber-reinforced polymer (CFRP) laminates (Di Ludovico et al, 2005). The study concluded that the upgrade technique used is structurally efficient in providing the damaged beams with stiffness and strength very close to that of the original undamaged beam. The authors conclude that the use of CFRP laminates can allow damaged PC girders to recover their original flexural capacity and stiffness. In this commentary, Chen contends that some of the test findings were not well clarified when the test results were compared with the predictions based on the authors' proposed design method. A closure response, written by the original authors, is appended to this discussion.

title: Seismic Retrofit of Octagonal Columns with Pedestal and One-Way Hinge at Base: Discussion.
authors: Himat T. Solanki
abstract: Recent earthquake experience has shown that the response of retrofitted bridges is generally satisfactory. However, many seismically-deficient bridges remain, notably those that are supported on piers that lack proper detailing to resist strong earthquakes. This brief discussion article comments on a recent study of seismic retrofit of bridge columns (Johnson et al, 2005). The original study used columns that are irregular both in the cross section and along the height, with the latter caused by the presence of a pedestal and a one-way hinge connection between the footing and the pedestal. The columns were subjected to a simulation of the 1994 Northridge Sylmar earthquake in the strong direction until failure. Results showed that the pedestal retrofit was successful in strengthening the pedestal sufficiently to shift the plastic hinging into the column. Johnson et al suggest that bond slip, shear deformation, and strain rate effects be accounted for in any effort to obtain a reasonable estimate of the push-over response of piers. Solanki's response addresses five topics: the hinges at the base of the columns; horizontal thrust (shear) and rotation of the hinges; other types of horizontal confinement that could have been used; hinge design and its impact on the cracking and peeling of the concrete cover over the transverse reinforcement; and how the retrofit condition for the structural members occurred. The original authors made a brief closure, which is appended to this discussion.

authors: Sri Sritharan
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by P.S. Baglin and R.H. Scott, published in this journal (Volume 97, Number 6, November-December 2000), is presented. The discusser commends the authors on their effort to investigate the behavior of external beam-column connections with nonlinear finite element models, and also supports their attempt to evaluate the effects of the main variables such as the column axial load on the joint behavior and joint capacity. The discusser, drawing on experience from a combination of experimental and analytical studies on bridge joints, provides comments on several issues relating to the authors' research. title: DEVELOPMENT OF BOND STRENGTH OF REINFORCEMENT STEEL IN SELF-CONSOLIDATING CONCRETE
authors: Y-W Chan; Yih‐Sharng Chen; Y-S Liu
abstract: This paper investigates the bond between self-consolidating concrete (SCC) and reinforcements. The bonding strengths of reinforcing bars were measured using full-scale reinforced concrete (RC) members of SCC and of ordinary concrete. The SCC members were cast without applying any consolidation, whereas the members of ordinary concrete were cast by conventional practice with substantial consolidation and vibration. Results showed that SCC members generated significantly higher bond to reinforcing bars than did ordinary concrete members. It was also found that the reduction in bond due to bleeding and inhomogeneous nature in the case of ordinary concrete was prevented in the case of SCC.

title: PLASTICITY MODEL FOR PREDICTING PUNCHING SHEAR STRENGTHS OF REINFORCED CONCRETE SLABS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Z P Bazant; H Solanki
abstract: Discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by W. Salim and W.M. Sebastian, published in this journal (Volume 99, Number 6, November-December 2002), is given. The discussers focus on the basic issue that using a purely plastic approach, such as punching shear failure, implies the absence of any deterministic size effect. An alternative, simpler approach using an approximation for the fixed diameter of generatrix to simplify computations is also suggested. Closure from the authors on these observations and recommendations is also included.

title: REDUCTION OF LATERAL REINFORCEMENT IN SEISMIC BEAM-COLUMN CONNECTION VIA APPLICATION OF STEEL FIBERS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: K. Sivakumar; Santhosh Sivaraj; N Arunachaiam
abstract: Discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by Z. Bayasi and M. Gebman, published in this journal (Volume 99, Number 6, November-December 2002), is presented. The discussers feel proper importance was not accorded to strength of concrete and the yield strength of steel in the original paper. Without consideration of the aforesaid parameters, it is quite difficult to comprehend the joint behavior in its entirety and to make a conclusive inference or comparison per se. The discussers also doubt the representation of the original structure into the experimental model of the authors as it sustains no column load and arrested vertical displacement at the beam-column junction. In closure, the authors respond to these points of contention.

title: EXCESSIVE STRAND END SLIP IN PRESTRESSED PILES. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Paul H. Kaar
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by M.F. Petrou et al., published in this journal (Volume 97, Number 5, September-October 2000), is presented. Closure relating to this question is provided.

title: USE OF HELIXES IN REINFORCED CONCRETE BEAMS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: G. Prince Arulraj; Seth Justin
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by M.N.S. Hadi and L.C. Schmidt, published in this journal (Volume 99, Number 2, March-April 2002), is presented. The discussers commend the authors of the original paper for their innovative idea of providing helical reinforcement in the compression zone of reinforced concrete beams to enhance the ductility and load-carrying capacity of beams. However, the discussers feel that the concept developed by the authors is applicable only for over-reinforced beams, and request that the authors respond with their view regarding the application of the concept for under-reinforced beams. title: SEISMIC BEHAVIOR OF SHORT COUPLING BEAMS WITH DIFFERENT REINFORCEMENT LAYOUTS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: T. P. Tassios; Marina L. Moretti; Antonios Bezas
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by L. Galano and A. Vignoli, published in this journal (Volume 97, Number 6, November-December 2000), is presented. title: FINITE ELEMENT MODELING OF REINFORCED CONCRETE BEAM-COLUMN CONNECTIONS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Artem Czkwianianc; Przemysław Bodzak
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by P.S. Baglin and R.H. Scott, published in this journal (Volume 97, Number 6, November-December 2000), is provided. title: BEHAVIOR OF LARGE-SCALE REINFORCED CONCRETE BEAMS WITH MINIMUM SHEAR REINFORCEMENT. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: M Khuntia
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by R.J. Frosch, published in this journal (Volume 97, Number 6, November-December 2000), is presented. The discusser commends the author on his efforts in conducting experimental research to predict the shear strength of large-size reinforced concrete (RC) members with minimum stirrups. However, the discusser has some reservations regarding the conclusions arrived at by the author and states that further test results and better explanations are needed. Closure by the author is provided.

title: EXPERIMENTAL BEHAVIOR OF FULL-DEPTH PRECAST CONCRETE PANELS FOR BRIDGE REHABILITATION. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: B Bakht; Aftab A. Mufti
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by M.A. Issa et al., published in this journal (Volume 97, Number 3, May-June 2000), is presented. The discussers seek clarification from the original authors on the methods they used to extrapolate the results of fatigue tests on quarter-scale models to full-size prototype structures in determining experimental behavior of full-depth precast concrete panels in bridge rehabilitation. Closure by the authors is provided.

title: IMPROVED ANALYTICAL MODEL FOR SHEAR STRENGTH OF CIRCULAR REINFORCED CONCRETE COLUMNS IN SEISMIC REGIONS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Evan C. Bentz; Michael P. Collins
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by M.J. Kowalsky and M.J.N. Priestley, published in this journal (Volume 97, Number 3, May-June 2000), is presented. While generally commending the authors presentation of an improved simple method to predict the shear strength of reinforced concrete columns, the discussers suggest that a small change to the alpha factor and the inclusion of a size effect term will make the proposed method in the original paper notably better. The discussion concludes with closure by the authors.

title: STRUT-AND-TIE MODELS AND FAILURE MECHANISMS FOR BAR DEVELOPMENT IN TENSION-TENSION-COMPRESSION NODAL ZONE
authors: S-G Hong
abstract: Strut-and-tie models and compatible failure mechanisms for bar development and anchorage failure in a tension-tension-compression nodal zone are presented on the basis of the classical theory of plasticity, in particular the normality rule, and the lower and upper bound theorems. The concrete is assumed as a rigid-perfectly plastic material obeying the modified Coulomb failure criteria with zero tension cut-off, and for bar/concrete interfaces, the simplest possible yield condition is assumed. The strut-and-tie models presented in this paper assume uniform compression fields, and the upper bound solutions introduce a new flexural type of failure mechanism for concrete crushing failure. The strut-and-tie models identify different failure modes related to bond strength and dependent on material strength and geometry.

title: Time-dependent properties of high-strength concrete with consideration for precast applications
authors: Alireza Mokhtarzadeh; Catherine French
abstract: This paper addresses the creep, shrinkage, and indirect permeability (water absorption) time-dependent properties of high-strength concrete. Tests were conducted on over 250 specimens to investigate the effects of variations in material composition and curing. Results were compared with American Concrete Institute (ACI) 209 relations for normal-strength concrete. Proposed modifications to the ACI 209 relations are given to represent the high-strength concrete data.

title: Effect of sand addition on properties of fiber-reinforced cement composites
authors: Yılmaz Akkaya; Alva Peled; Jeffrey D. Picka; Surendra P. Shah
abstract: Effect of sand addition on the mechanical properties of cast and extruded polyvinyl acetate fiber-reinforced cement composites was investigated. The addition of sand increased the strength of the plain cement paste, but decreased the mechanical performance of the fiber-reinforced cement composites. To understand this behavior of the composites, microstructural properties such as fiber dispersion, alignment, and composite porosity were investigated and statistically quantified. The reduction in the performance of the composites with sand was found to be a result of the differences in fiber dispersion, composite porosity, and interaction between the fiber and the matrix. Fiber clumping, increase in the size and number of fiber-free areas, and higher matrix porosity were observed in the composites when sand was used.

title: Empirical models to predict concrete expansion caused by sulfate attack
authors: Kimberly E. Kurtis; Paulo J.M. Monteiro; Samer Madanat
abstract: The development of empirical models to predict concrete expansion produced by sulfate attack is described. Data collected by the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation over more than 40 years of nonaccelerated testing form the basis for the model. In the nonaccelerated test program, concrete cylinders were continuously submerged at room temperature in 2.1% sodium sulfate solution, which corresponds to severe field exposure conditions. Expansion measurements were made periodically. Over 8,000 expansion measurements were collected for 114 specimens cast from 51 different mixtures. Analysis of the data showed the significance of water-to-cement ratio (w/c) and C3A content of the cement, with the data revealing distinct behavior for mixtures containing cements with low C3A content (less than 8%) and high C3A content (greater than 10%). As a result, two models are proposed to predict expansion by sulfate attack as a function of w/c, duration of exposure, and C3A content. The random effects method was used to capture unobserved heterogeneity in the data set, and the results from a simple regression and a regression including the random effects method are compared.

title: High content of fly ash (class F) in extruded cementitious composites
authors: Alva Peled; Michèle F. Cyr; Surendra P. Shah
abstract: This paper presents mechanical properties and durability of extruded fiber-reinforced cement composites that contain a high percentage of Class F fly ash. The fly ash was examined as a replacement for cement in a plain cement matrix and composites containing polyvinyl alcohol, glass, acrylic (PAN), polypropylene, or cellulose fibers. Accelerated aging was used to study the effect of fly ash on the durability of the different systems. It was shown that fly ash improves the flexural performance of the extruded composite. The extent of this improvement varied with fiber type. PAN, glass, and cellulose fibers were most affected by the use of fly ash. The greatest improvement in both flexural strength and ductility was obtained for 28-day moist-cured composites containing PAN fibers when as much as 70%, by volume, of the cement was replaced with fly ash. In this case, a five-fold increase in toughness and an approximately 20% improvement in strength were observed for steam-cured composites.

title: FAILURE AND STRENGTH OF HIGH-STRENGTH CONCRETE COLUMNS SUBJECTED TO ECCENTRIC LOADS
authors: Jong‐Hyeon Lee; H-S Son
abstract: The objective of this paper is to verify the basic design rules of high-strength concrete columns. Thirty-two column specimens were tested to investigate structural behavior and strength of eccentrically loaded reinforced concrete tied columns. Main variables included in this test program were concrete compressive strength, steel amount, eccentricity, and slenderness ratio. The concrete compressive strength varied from 34.9 MPa to 98.2 MPa, and the longitudinal steel ratios were between 1.13% and 5.51%. Test results of column sectional strength are compared with the results of analyses by American Concrete Institute (ACI) rectangular stress block, trapezoidal stress block, and modified rectangular stress block. Axial force-moment-curvature analysis is also performed for predicting axial load-moment strength and compared with the test results. The ACI rectangular stress block provides overestimated column strengths for the lightly reinforced high-strength column specimens. The calculated strengths by moment-curvature analyses are highly affected by k3 values of the concrete stress-strain curve. Observed failure mode, concrete ultimate strain, and stress block parameters are discussed.

title: ANOTHER LOOK AT CRACKING AND CRACK CONTROL IN REINFORCED CONCRETE. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Hans Gesund
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by R.J. Frosh, published in this journal (Volume 96, Number 3, May-June 1999), is presented. The discussion brings up two questions. The first considers the appropriateness of the recommended equation for a parking garage incorporating epoxy-coated reinforcement. The second question is in regards to the use of reinforcement spacing rather than bar size to control cracking. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: STRENGTHENING REINFORCED CONCRETE BEAMS USING FIBER-REINFORCED POLYMER (FRP) LAMINATES. DISCUSSION
authors: Guilherme Sales Soares de Azevedo Melo
corresponding_authors: Guilherme Sales Soares de Azevedo Melo
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by N.F. Grace, G.A. Sayed, A.K. Soliman, and K.R. Saleh, published in this journal (Volume 96, Number 5, September-October 1999), is presented. The discusser points out that in 9 of the 14 beams tested by the authors, the fiber-reinforced polymer (FRP) materials were positioned up to the top part of the beam, almost encapsulating the beams. He points out that the situation in practice is not quite always the same and that this solution could not be broadly used, as the slab does not allow the laminates (fibers, sheets, or plates) to be positioned up to the top of the beam.

title: EXPERIMENTAL EVALUATION OF STRUT-AND-TIE MODEL APPLIED TO DEEP BEAM WITH OPENING. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Johan Blaauwendraad
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by B.S. Maxwell and J.E. Breen, published in this journal (Volume 97, Number 1, January-February 2000), is presented. The discusser claims that the authors tend to overestimate the margin between the analysis and the test results. Thus, the discussion examines the difference between test result and predicted strength and the difference between the first and second tests. It concludes that the beam with the mixed reinforcement systems can hold the same experimental failure load as the systems do separately if one could perfectly halve the reinforcement. Larger stiffness and strength in the test are due to the fact that far more reinforcement was applied than required. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: ARCH ACTION IN REINFORCED CONCRETE BEAMS--A RATIONAL PREDICTION OF SHEAR STRENGTH. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: J. L. Merritt
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by D. Kim, W. Kim, and R.N. White, published in this journal (Volume 96, Number 4, July-August 1999), is presented. The discusser presents a summary of his own approach for shear strength predictions and raises a number of questions and issues on this problem. The discusser's results indicate that correlation between his predictions and experimental results began to break down for reinforcing ratios higher than approximately 2%. The discusser also found some dependence of shear strength on compression reinforcing ratio, with shear strength decreasing as compression steel ratio increased. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: HORIZONTAL SHEAR STRENGTH OF INDIRECTLY LOADED COMPOSITE CONCRETE BEAMS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: A. K. Patnaik
abstract: A discussion of a paper with aforementioned title by K.H. Tan, L.W. Guan, X. Lu, and T.Y. Lim, published in this journal (Volume 96, Number 4, July-August 1999), is presented. The discussion provides clarification of certain issues raised by authors, particularly as they have referred to discusser's earlier work, pointing out dissimilarity between surface condition of authors' test specimens and American Concrete Institute (ACI) requirement of a roughened interface. The discusser maintains that statement, the ultimate horizontal shear strength of composite beams can be significantly lower than ACI Code provisions is inaccurate and must be disregarded. Discussion is followed by closure from authors.

title: LOAD-DEFLECTION BEHAVIOR OF SMOOTH DOWELS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Pasko
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by S.S. Mannava; T.D. Bush, Jr.; and A.R. Kukreti, published in this journal (Volume 96, Number 6, November-December 1999), is presented. The discusser maintains that the analysis of dowel action in concrete by linear elastic methods and static tests is interesting, but has not been very useful in describing performance of dowel joints in concrete pavements. On the other hand, empirical dynamic tests have led to rules of thumb for design that the highway community has readily accepted and which have given reliable performance in the field. The discusser believes that the authors, in their background, understate the significance of previous work by Teller and Cashell (1958) and that the only way of evaluating alternative load transfer devices is by comparing dynamic testing between dowels and the proposed devices. Today, several new alternatives are being used, such as plate dowels, square dowels, plastic fiber composite dowels, and plastic sleeved dowels. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: BEHAVIOR OF SLENDER HIGH-STRENGTH COLUMNS
authors: Priyan Mendis
abstract: The use of high-strength concrete (HSC) with compressive strengths exceeding 50 MPa is becoming popular worldwide. In most cases, the use of HSC in columns allows smaller cross sections to be adopted, implying that slenderness effects are enhanced. This outcome means that consideration and evaluation of slenderness effects in HSC columns are more critical than in normal-strength concrete columns. This paper reviews the applicability of the existing moment magnification method given in the American Concrete Institute and Australian codes to cover the slenderness effects in HSC columns up to 100 MPa. A numerical method is suggested to conduct more accurate analyses of slender columns. Finally, the analytical results are compared with the experimental results.

title: SEISMIC PERFORMANCE OF RECTANGULAR BRIDGE COLUMNS WITH MODERATE CONFINEMENT. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Santiago Pujol; Mete A. Sözen
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by N.I. Wehbe, M.S. Saiidi, and D.H. Sanders, published in this journal (Volume 96, Number 2, March-April 1999), is presented. The discussers maintain that theoretical and measured values of initial stiffness of reinforced concrete members may not be in total agreement, even in a controlled laboratory environment, and suggest eliminating the effect of footing flexibility. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: CORROSION EFFECTS ON BOND STRENGTH IN REINFORCED CONCRETE. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: C.M. Hansson
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by K. Stanish, R.D. Hooton, and S.J. Pantazopoulou, published in this journal (Volume 96, Number 6, November-December 1999), is presented. The discussion raises objections to the use of impressed current to accelerate corrosion for the study of the effects of corrosion, stressing the differences between naturally occurring corrosion and the corrosion products that are developed using an impressed current technique. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: MEASUREMENT OF D2O IN WATER USING 2H(Y,N)1H REACTION
authors: Mehrnaz Rahimi; H. Peyrovan; Abdolmajid Izadpanah
abstract: Utilization of Photodisintegration reaction of Deuterium, 2 H(γ,n) 1 H, is a precise technique for determining the percentage of 2 H in tritiated and natural water. The 23 Na(n,γ) 24 Na reaction is a suitable γ-source for producing the 2 H(γ,n) 1 H reaction. Tehran Research Reactor was used as a neutron source for producing 24 Na isotopes. The BF3 detectors were used to detect the neutron emission of H2 content of water. We obtained a linear calibration plot by repeating the experiment with many samples of different concentrations of tritiated water. With this simple portable apparatus which have been used for this purpose for the first time, and corresponding linear plot, we can monitor and determine easily and accurately the 2 H concentration of an unknown sample.

title: SHEAR STRENGTH OF REINFORCED CONCRETE DEEP BEAMS WITH END ANCHORAGE FAILURE
authors: S-G Hong; SY Kim; N-K Hong
abstract: This paper focuses on the shear strength of deep beams combined with anchorage failure, based on upper bound solutions in the theory of plasticity. The solutions showed that the shear strength combined with anchorage failure is lower than other shear strength due to web crushing in some range of design parameters. The effects of shear span ratio, ratio of embedment length of bars beyond support to beam depth, and vertical reinforcement ratio on the failure modes and strengths were also investigated. An experiment was performed to compare with the plastic solutions and displayed good agreement with those of theoretical results. Lastly, this paper proposes a range of design parameters for ductile failure mode of reinforced concrete deep beams, which ensures a safe detailing of end anchorage for the flexural failure of deep beams.

title: FLEXURAL STRENGTHENING WITH CARBON FIBER-REINFORCED POLYMER COMPOSITES OF PRELOADED FULL-SCALE GIRDERS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Renata Kotynia; M. Kamińska
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by M. Shahawy et al., published in this journal (Volume 98, Number 5, September-October 2001), is given. While commending the authors for an interesting paper and acknowledging the importance of conducting an experimental program to further the quality of strengthening reinforced concrete beams using CFRP fabrics, the discussers feel that certain aspects of the authors' paper should be discussed and relevant issues addressed. These issues primarily relate to the test program presented in the paper and are dealt with in some detail. In closure, the authors respond to these points.

title: EFFECT OF CONCRETE STRENGTH AND MINIMUM STIRRUPS ON SHEAR STRENGTH OF LARGE MEMBERS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: M Khuntia
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by D. Angelakos, E.C. Bentz, and M.P. Collins, published in this journal (Volume 98, Number 3, May-June 2001), is presented. The discusser commends the authors for conducting a very useful experimental study on the behavior of large-size reinforced concrete (RC) members that includes normal- and high-strength concrete. The discusser agrees with the authors that the present ACI Code provisions on shear strength of RC members are inadequate and adds some additional comments relating to this topic. Closure from the authors is provided.

title: SEISMIC PERFORMANCE AND RETROFIT OF STEEL PILE TO CONCRETE CAP CONNECTIONS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Marotta
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by A.A. Shama, J.B. Mander et al., published in this journal (Volume 99, Number 1, January-February 2002), is presented. The discusser comments that he is unfamiliar with the method used by the authors to test their example, and questions whether it conforms to current practice in the eastern U.S. Closure from the authors is also provided.

title: EVALUATION OF SHEAR DESIGN PROCEDURES FOR REINFORCED CONCRETE MEMBERS UNDER AXIAL COMPRESSION. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: M Khuntia
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by P.R. Gupta and M.P. Collins, published in this journal (Volume 98, Number 4, July-August 2001), is given. The discusser commends the authors for conducting a valuable experimental study on reinforced concrete (RC) elements under axial compression and for making important recommendations dealing with current ACI procedures. A simple explanation is offered to complement the conclusions reached in the paper relating to the ACI simplified and detailed methods and AASHTO-LRFD method for evaluation of shear design procedures for RC members under axial compression. In closure, the authors respond to the applicability of this explanation as it relates to conclusions reached in their work.

title: CONFINEMENT OF HIGH-STRENGTH CONCRETE WITH WELDED WIRE REINFORCEMENT. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Arias Herrera
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with aforementioned title by N. Lambert-Aikhionbare and S.W. Tabsh, published in this journal (Volume 98, Number 5, September-October 2001), is presented. The discusser raises a question relative to one statement by authors in which they posit, the constructability of columns transversely reinforced with 2-D welded wire reinforcement grids may not be a difficult task. The discusser states that it would be interesting to know if authors attempted to cast full-size columns, particularly columns in order of 2.5-3.0 m long, in a vertical position to confirm validity of their statement. In closure, authors respond to discusser's point.

title: CONFINEMENT MODEL FOR AXIALLY LOADED CONCRETE CONFINED BY CIRCULAR FIBER-REINFORCED POLYMER TUBES. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Esneyder Montoya
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title, by A.Z. Fam and S.H. Rizkalla, published in this journal (Volume 98, Number 4, July-August 2001), is presented. The discusser raises a number of points relating to the authors' establishment of a second-order polynomial regression for the average lateral-axial strain curves of concrete cylinders tested by Gardner (1969), and believes that the analytical expression for the constant C used in their work does not reflect well the actual behavior of confined concrete cylinders where concrete dilation is delayed due to the action of increased radial pressure. In closure, the authors thank the discusser for his critical review and expand, in more detail, on the modeling of Poisson's ratio of concrete under different confinement levels.

title: STIFFNESS MODELING OF REINFORCED CONCRETE BEAM-COLUMNS FOR FRAME ANALYSIS. DISCUSSION
authors: M Khuntia
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by S.S.F. Mehanny, H. Kuramoto, and G.G. Deierlein, published in this journal (Volume 98, Number 2, March-April 2001), is presented. The discusser congratulates the authors for suggesting stiffness models for reinforced concrete beam-columns for frame analysis and agrees that the present ACI Code provisions on effective stiffnesses of beams and columns are inadequate for frame analysis. However, a critical review of the suggested model on flexural stiffness shows that the model has some important limitations. The aim of this discussion is to point out these limitations, and offer some explanation and information that will hopefully complement the paper under consideration.

title: ANALYTICAL AND FIELD INVESTIGATION OF LATERAL LOAD DISTRIBUTION IN CONCRETE SLAB-ON-GIRDER BRIDGES. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Michael J. Abrahams
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by M. Shahawy and D. Huang, published in this journal (Volume 98, Number 4, July-August 2001), is presented. The original paper compared results of the authors' investigation of the live-load distribution in girder bridges with those found in AASHTO-LRFD specifications, concluding that the LRFD specifications are in error as they are more conservative than the authors' results. The discusser makes several comments relating to the authors' work, stating the need to include bridges without diaphragms in future research in order to make their findings consistent with the AASHTO-LRFD specifications. In closure, the authors respond to these comments and clarify their findings somewhat.

title: BEHAVIOR OF REINFORCED CONCRETE WALLS WITH WELDED WIRE MESH SUBJECTED TO CYCLIC LOADING. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Roy H. Reiterman; Rex Richardson; T A Mize
abstract: A discussion of an earlier paper with the aforementioned title by P. Riva and A. Franchi, published in this journal (Volume 98, Number 3, May-June 2001), is presented. The discussers note that there are many inconsistencies in comparing different materials and different sizes of materials in the original paper, making its findings somewhat biased towards the authors' 'favorite materials.' There does not seem to be a logical method used for comparing the same materials and sizes with the various strength levels, let alone test methods that conform to ASTM standards. Closure from the authors is provided, responding to these points.

title: STRENGTHENING OF TWO-WAY SLABS USING STEEL PLATES. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: H Solanki
abstract: A discussion of earlier paper with the aforementioned title by U. Ebead and H. Marzouk, published in this journal (Volume 99, Number 1, January-February 2002), is presented. The discusser commends the authors on their paper and agrees that a steel plate would certainly increase the ultimate strength of the control specimen. However, the discusser notes that the authors do not explain the inconsistency between Specimen A1 and Specimen A3 in their research. This point is expanded upon, and closure from the authors is also provided.

title: DESIGN OF REINFORCED CONCRETE FLEXURAL SECTIONS BY UNIFIED DESIGN APPROACH. DISCUSSIONS AND CLOSURE
authors: Jcm Toro; Richard W. Furlong
abstract: Two discussions of a paper with the aforementioned title by J.A. Munshi, published in this journal (Volume 95, Number 5, September-October 1998), are presented. The first discusser recommends an alternative method for calculating the upper limit for reinforcement ratio of flexural sections. The second discusser agrees that the differences between the unified design approach and the current 3/4 rho balanced approach are explained very clearly by the author. However, he maintains that the similarity between the two approaches should be emphasized, lest those unfamiliar with them might ignore the clarity and logic offered by current practice when applied to both reliable strength and ductility. Discussion is followed by closure from the author.

title: EXPERIMENTAL STUDIES ON HIGH-STRENGTH CONCRETE DEEP BEAMS. DISCUSSION
authors: M. Nasser Darwish
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by S. Foster and R.I. Gilbert, published in this journal (Volume 95, Number 4, July-August 1998), is presented. The discusser observes that the authors' tests may represent actual deep beam conditions, but as tension failure controls the effects of the variables under consideration, web reinforcement and concrete strength may have been obscured.

title: PERFORMANCE OF EXISTING BRIDGE COLUMNS UNDER CYCLIC LOADING--PART 2: ANALYSIS AND COMPARISON WITH THEORY. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Nadim Wehbe; M S Saiidi
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by O.A. Jaradat, D.I. McLean, and M.L. Marsh, published in this journal (Volume 96, Number 1, January-February 1999), is presented. The discussers maintain that the results presented by the authors have four shortcomings: the point of shear failure is not clearly defined; the displacement ductilities, as measured and reported, are not suitable for the evaluation of shear strength; the specified M/VD ratio should not be emphasized as a significant parameter; and the data show that the UCSD equation overestimates the shear capacity. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: FLEXURAL BEHAVIOR OF CONCRETE BEAMS REINFORCED WITH DEFORMED FIBER REINFORCED PLASTIC REINFORCING RODS. DISCUSSION
authors: Edward G. Nawy
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by R. Masmoudi, M. Theriault, and B. Benmokrane, published in this journal (Volume 95, Number 6, November-December 1998), is presented. The discusser stresses that the brittle behavior of the deformed plastic bars at ultimate state of failure requires that only 30-35% of the ultimate load be utilized at the working load level. Additional reserve strength has to be allowed in the design, if the usual expressions for flexural design of concrete members are to be used. In this manner, serviceability conditions as defined by crack control and deflection control can be within tolerable limits.

title: UNIFIED MINIMUM FLEXURAL REINFORCEMENT REQUIREMENTS FOR REINFORCED AND PRESTRESSED CONCRETE MEMBERS. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Catalina Ospina
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by C.L. Freyermuth and B.O. Aalami, published in this journal (Volume 94, Number 4, July-August 1997), is presented. The discussion addresses some observations regarding flexural capacity, brittle and ductile behavior, adequate crack control, and minimum reinforcement limits, in light of published test results and existing code provisions. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: STRESS DISTRIBUTION AND CRACKING BEHAVIOR AT ANCHORAGE ZONES IN PRESTRESSED CONCRETE MEMBERS. DISCUSSION
authors: Gregor P. Wollmann; J E Breen
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by B.H. Oh, D.H. Lim, and S.S. Park, published in this journal (Volume 94, Number 5, September-October 1997), is presented. The discussers offer a few comments and clarifications to the paper and, at the same time, provide some background information on the new anchorage zone specifications adopted by the American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials (AASHTO) for inclusion in the U.S. Standard Bridge Specifications. The specifications divide the tendon anchorage zone into a local and general anchorage zone, and should lead to correctly designed and reinforced tendon anchorage zones.

authors: Alan H. Mattock
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by S. Foster, R.E. Powell, and H.S. Selim, published in this journal (Volume 93, Number 5, September-October 1996), is presented. The discusser maintains that the authors found that the ACI 318 shear friction design method used to calculate the shear strength yielded generally unconservative results, because they failed to limit the shear strength as specified in Code Section 11.9.3.2.1. The shear strength limit also prevents congestion of reinforcement in corbels.

title: ANALYTICAL COMPUTATION OF THE PUNCHING STRENGTH OF REINFORCED CONCRETE. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Iaem Shehata
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by P. Menetrey, published in this journal (Volume 93, Number 5, September-October 1996) is presented. The discusser argues that the proposed model for the analysis of punching shear in reinforced concrete lacks rationality and realism and that it is neither an upper bound solution nor a lower bound solution. Furthermore, he maintains that the dowel effect (shear transferred by reinforcing bars crossing a concrete interface) contribution should not be taken into account. Discussion is followed by closure from the author.

title: EXPERIMENTAL INVESTIGATION ON SHEAR ENHANCEMENT TYPES OF HIGH-STRENGTH CONCRETE PLATES. DISCUSSION AND CLOSURE
authors: Sdb Alexander
abstract: A discussion of a paper with the aforementioned title by H. Marzouk and D. Jiang, published in this journal (Volume 94, Number 1, January-February 1997), is presented. The discussion claims that the test specimens would have carried approximately 20% more load had the reinforcement been anchored with hooks or welded end plates and maintains that insufficient anchorage of the flexural reinforcement masked the effectiveness of the shear reinforcement at increasing both the strength and ductility of connections. Discussion is followed by closure from the authors.

title: CYCLIC BEHAVIOR OF HIGH-STRENGTH CONCRETE SHORT BEAMS WITH LOWER AMOUNT OF FLEXURAL REINFORCEMENT
authors: I-K Fang; Wang Cs; K-L Hong
abstract: Experimental investigation of the cyclic behavior of high-strength concrete (HSC) short beams with lower flexural reinforcement ratio is reported. Fifteen cantilever beam specimens were subjected to monotonic loading and various types of cyclic laodings. The main variables included shear span-to-depth ratio, compressive strength of concrete, and loading histories. The compressive strength of concrete varied from 32 MPa to 70 MPa. Test results indicated that the dispalacement ductility factor of HSC is about 5 to 6. The trend of degradation in strength and stiffness, as well as the energy dissipation capacity of beam specimens, became more pronounced as the shear stress level in the plastic hinge region increased.

title: EFFECTIVE PRESTRESS FORCE IN CONTINUOUS POST-TENSIONED BEAMS
authors: Ned H. Burns; Todd Helwig; T Tsuijimoto
abstract: Changes in force due to friction in unbonded tendons were observed in 2-span continuous post-tensioned girders at various stages in the stressing and loading history. Following transfer, diffferent holding forces existed at the ends of each of the two girders tested (one with greater span/depth ratio than the other). This difference remained after a cyclic loading program (including post-cracking) of several thousand repetitions of service load patterns.

title: CONSTITUTIVE MODEL FOR REINFORCED FINITE ELEMENT ANALYSIS
authors: Nick Stevens; S. M. Uzumeri; Michael P. Collins; George T. Will
abstract: The paper extends modified compression field theory (MCFT) so that it is more suitable for finite element implementation. The modifications eliminate the need to check that average concrete tensile stresses can be transmitted across the cracks. This is achieved by working strictly in terms of average stresses and strains for both the concrete and the reinforcing steel. Appropriate stress-versus-strain relationships are proposed which take into account the amount, size, distribution, and oreintation of the reinforcing steel. The effect of these modifications is an improvement in the simplicity and generality of MCFT with no loss of accuracy. The proposed constitutive model is implemented into a finite element formulation resulting in a powerful and efficient tool for the analysis of two-dimensional reinforced concrete structural elements.
